“By the end of the reporting period, KeRRA had budgeted to maintain 28,837 kilometres of roads but had managed to maintain 8,063 kilometres or 28 per cent of the target,” read the report by the road’s regulator.
The score is much lower than other agencies including the Kenya Urban Roads Authority, which had set out to maintain some 1,796km of roads but maintained 1,170km or 65 per cent of the target over the same period.



