KeRRA funds
The KeRRA funds are spent in collaboration with constituency development committees where MPs have significant influence, a key setback for the agency, according to Kenya Roads Board (KRB) insiders.
A senior manager at the road’s regulator, who did not want his identity revealed for fear of fightback from legislators, said the agency’s performance would remain poor as long as MPs still have a say on how they spend road maintenance cash.
“They have a lot of problems even bidding for roads since MPs push for who to be awarded and which roads should be maintained. They end up spreading the funds so thin that they only manage to murram most of the roads which are quickly damaged every rainy season,” the source intimated.
Road networks
The Kenya National Highways Authority (KeNHA) scored highest at 81 per cent for maintaining 13,344km of the targeted 16,580km of its road networks using the KRB fund distributes.



