Even the counties, which usually perform poorly in road maintenance did better than the KeRRA with the devolved units achieving 68 per cent of its targeted 12,614km of roads for maintenance over the period.
The rural roads agency is the second-highest recipient of the multi-billion fund collected from fuel purchases yearly. It received Sh12.4 billion out of the Sh69 billion collected in the year to June 2019.
The KeNHA was allocated the highest at Sh23.6 billion from the fund due to its lengthy networks of roads under its watch.
The road agencies have recently been on the spot for failing to properly account for the multibillion levy for road maintenance, casting doubt on whether the funds are directed to the intended purposes, which is to keep roads in good shape.
